We've been talking a lot about video conferencing software, and I think that a lot has been done over the last few weeks to really advance fandom's engagement with these tools.

408
00:30:05,180 --> 00:30:13,260
Zoom has come under fire over the last week or so for various bits of bad practice to do with privacy.

409
00:30:13,260 --> 00:30:18,120
I don't want to give the impression here that I don't think people should use Zoom.

410
00:30:18,120 --> 00:30:23,340
Zoom is an incredible piece of software that's really helping people keep their mental health and their communication lines open.

411
00:30:23,340 --> 00:30:24,600
I think that's great.

412
00:30:24,600 --> 00:30:34,000
I do think it's worth being aware of some of Zoom's potential pitfalls and protecting yourself against them if it's something you mind.

413
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:36,480
And if it's not something you mind, obviously go wild.

414
00:30:36,880 --> 00:30:39,020
But recently there have been a few bits of controversy.

415
00:30:39,020 --> 00:30:46,100
Notably, they had some Facebook data in their iOS app that was sending data back to Facebook.

416
00:30:47,140 --> 00:30:59,160
They had said that their chats were end-to-end encrypted, but it turned out that their encryption is not end-to-end and is in fact based on a slightly different encryption method to the method that they had said they used.

417
00:30:59,160 --> 00:31:05,880
Their macOS installer abuses pre-installation scripts to install itself without letting you see what's it going to install.

418
00:31:06,120 --> 00:31:17,200
And a few months ago, I think actually maybe a year ago, they had installed a local web server on every Mac they installed on, which let them reinstall their app even after you'd uninstalled it.

419
00:31:17,380 --> 00:31:29,780
It is worth saying that they have published a blog post in the last few days that outline a 90-day plan to address a lot of these privacy concerns and that they are working very hard to address them.

420
00:31:29,780 --> 00:31:35,820
And I appreciate those points got more and more technical and less and less understandable as time goes on.

421
00:31:36,020 --> 00:31:37,780
I will put links in the show notes.

422
00:31:37,780 --> 00:31:43,920
And as I say, I want to emphasise that I am advising people be careful rather than stop using it altogether.

423
00:31:43,920 --> 00:31:50,200
But both of you, to what extent do you think this is a thing we need to be super concerned about?

424
00:31:50,200 --> 00:31:54,580
And to what extent do you think that this is something that we just need to be mindful of?

425
00:31:54,580 --> 00:32:06,700
I think that a lot of the people who are making the most noise about Zoom use either A, Facebook, or B, emailing lists, both of which are notably less secure than Zoom.

426
00:32:06,700 --> 00:32:12,660
So these Zooms are clearly a bunch of white boys, honestly.

427
00:32:12,660 --> 00:32:14,500
They started this company.

428
00:32:14,500 --> 00:32:16,920
They made a good product.

429
00:32:16,920 --> 00:32:18,780
They did not care about privacy.

430
00:32:18,780 --> 00:32:22,460
And they clearly failed in three different areas.

431
00:32:22,460 --> 00:32:30,740
The first is that they have a load of kind of corporate spying stuff so that your boss can spy on you, which is, I think, fairly normal for corporate software.

432
00:32:30,740 --> 00:32:38,800
They didn't care in the sense that other people's security things, they just kind of worked around if that way they got to make a better product.

433
00:32:38,800 --> 00:32:44,720
So they basically went, aha, can we make a better product by entering operating systems by the back door?

434
00:32:44,720 --> 00:32:45,340
Yes, we can.

435
00:32:45,340 --> 00:32:46,120
We should do that.

436
00:32:46,120 --> 00:32:54,020
And the third is they left great gaping holes in their security accidentally while they were busy trying to make a better product.

437
00:32:54,020 --> 00:32:55,840
And they ended up with a better product.

438
00:32:55,840 --> 00:32:59,900
And now they're going, OK, so clearly everyone's using our product because it's better.

439
00:32:59,900 --> 00:33:05,360
We should probably go back and fix those holes we left in it, which I think is fair.

440
00:33:06,080 --> 00:33:09,500
It's not the best way to behave, but it is better.

441
00:33:09,500 --> 00:33:13,280
It is noticeably better for any video chat over eight people.

442
00:33:13,280 --> 00:33:18,320
And it's probably better for most of the ones under that, except possibly Microsoft Teams.

443
00:33:18,320 --> 00:33:21,960
People think Microsoft Teams is very good, but everything else is definitely worse.

444
00:33:21,960 --> 00:33:23,300
I will agree with you.

445
00:33:23,300 --> 00:33:27,220
I think that they have clearly made a good product and now they are fixing it.

446
00:33:27,440 --> 00:33:30,900
I think part of the reason they are fixing it is because there has been so much criticism.

447
00:33:30,900 --> 00:33:33,140
So I do think, I do think strong.

448
00:33:33,140 --> 00:33:34,000
Absolutely.

449
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:34,740
Absolutely.

450
00:33:34,740 --> 00:33:36,400
They wouldn't be fixing it if they weren't forced to.

451
00:33:36,400 --> 00:33:39,320
Yeah, I think, I think strong criticism is an important part of that.

452
00:33:39,320 --> 00:33:41,540
And that is the spirit in which I criticize.

453
00:33:41,540 --> 00:33:47,720
So I've been using Zoom for ages because it just worked better than all the alternatives.

454
00:33:47,720 --> 00:33:51,660
So I mean, I do a lot of video conferencing anyway, and I do a lot of video conferencing

455
00:33:51,660 --> 00:33:55,380
with people who have pretty terrible internet connections.

456
00:33:55,380 --> 00:33:59,240
And Zoom was noticeably better than any of the alternatives for that.

457
00:33:59,240 --> 00:34:00,260
It was better than WebEx.

458
00:34:00,260 --> 00:34:01,700
It was better than Google Hangouts.

459
00:34:01,700 --> 00:34:03,220
It was better than Skype.

460
00:34:03,220 --> 00:34:07,280
I mean, we didn't try running work chats on Facebook Messenger, but I suspect it's better than that.

461
00:34:07,280 --> 00:34:08,960
Oh God, Facebook Messenger is awful.

462
00:34:08,960 --> 00:34:09,700
Oh my God.

463
00:34:09,700 --> 00:34:15,340
So I'm quite, I think I feel I'm quite relaxed about it in that I know it does some terrible things,

464
00:34:15,340 --> 00:34:18,420
but I sort of assume all software is doing some terrible things,

465
00:34:18,720 --> 00:34:23,400
unless I'm using one of the real, like good open source ones that have, you know,

466
00:34:23,400 --> 00:34:25,360
been built from the ground up for that kind of thing.

467
00:34:25,360 --> 00:34:28,740
So I'm glad people are aware of these things.

468
00:34:28,740 --> 00:34:31,560
I'm glad people are pointing them out and that they fix them.

469
00:34:31,560 --> 00:34:34,600
But otherwise I'm not too wound up about it.

470
00:34:34,600 --> 00:34:38,980
I should say I do use Microsoft Teams a lot now because all our work,

471
00:34:38,980 --> 00:34:43,560
all our work, well, everything basically is moved to Office 365.

472
00:34:44,720 --> 00:34:49,960
And Microsoft Teams just works really nicely and it just works a lot of the time.

473
00:34:49,960 --> 00:34:55,900
We haven't run a really huge event in it yet, but we are swapping our weekly seminars to Microsoft Teams.

474
00:34:55,900 --> 00:35:00,140
And they will be, you know, we sometimes have got up to 100 people in there.

475
00:35:00,140 --> 00:35:01,160
So I'll see how that works.

476
00:35:01,160 --> 00:35:02,200
It's very corporate.

477
00:35:02,200 --> 00:35:04,660
I want to say two things in reaction to that.

478
00:35:04,660 --> 00:35:09,780
I'm going to push back slightly on the thing you said about every software doing this.

479
00:35:09,860 --> 00:35:12,740
I think Zoom is more egregious than most so far.

480
00:35:12,740 --> 00:35:15,220
I think the point about Facebook is a reasonable one.

481
00:35:15,220 --> 00:35:19,460
Facebook are obviously in some ways much more egregious than almost anyone else.

482
00:35:19,460 --> 00:35:23,860
But at this point, my neighborhood community group is on Facebook.

483
00:35:23,860 --> 00:35:28,580
My streets WhatsApp group is obviously hosted on a Facebook owned service.

484
00:35:28,580 --> 00:35:31,980
All of the local shops put their opening times and announcements on Facebook.

485
00:35:32,240 --> 00:35:40,220
So at this point, I must use Facebook to take part in my community, which is something I resent hugely, but does appear to be distressingly true.

486
00:35:40,220 --> 00:35:42,520
I will say Microsoft Teams is very good.

487
00:35:42,520 --> 00:35:48,380
I think that the problem there is obviously you need an Office 365 subscription, which not everyone has.

488
00:35:48,380 --> 00:35:54,340
I don't think Microsoft have made any overtures towards making Teams free to use.

489
00:35:54,340 --> 00:36:01,060
I suspect because they see Skype as their consumer chatting tool and they don't see Microsoft schemes as something they need to open up.

490
00:36:01,060 --> 00:36:06,940
But whereas Zoom, I believe, have relaxed a lot of their restrictions in light of the coronavirus pandemic.

491
00:36:06,940 --> 00:36:08,520
Oh, Alison is shaking her head.

492
00:36:08,520 --> 00:36:13,080
Teams doesn't have a free tier, but only the host needs to have the paid account.

493
00:36:13,080 --> 00:36:15,080
I think that's the important thing.

494
00:36:15,080 --> 00:36:20,620
And Office 365 is not expensive if there's just one of you and you're using it for this sort of thing.

495
00:36:20,620 --> 00:36:24,800
People kept saying with the Zoom account, because I got a paid Zoom account to do the first Thursday,

496
00:36:24,800 --> 00:36:26,560
oh, do you want some help with the cost?

497
00:36:26,560 --> 00:36:33,900
And I said, well, compared to getting a tube ticket to the pub and buying one pint of beer, it was there.

498
00:36:33,900 --> 00:36:35,040
That was the amount.

499
00:36:35,040 --> 00:36:40,540
So these tools are not expensive compared to the life we've just given up to get them.

500
00:36:40,540 --> 00:36:42,780
So, yeah, that is my crumble.

501
00:36:43,100 --> 00:36:48,480
And also nobody cares about your video chats and the pub isn't exactly a secure environment either.

502
00:36:48,480 --> 00:36:50,600
I don't think the cabinet should be using Zoom.

503
00:36:50,600 --> 00:36:53,300
I did think that was a bit shocking.

504
00:36:53,300 --> 00:36:56,820
And no doubt they've done magic cabinet things.

505
00:36:56,820 --> 00:37:00,600
But seeing as they don't for anything else, it doesn't seem very likely that they really have this either.

506
00:37:00,800 --> 00:37:07,860
Well, that's one other thing, which is because Zoom uses a predictable naming scheme for archives of the chats,

507
00:37:07,860 --> 00:37:14,080
the Washington Post was able to reverse engineer it to see stuff like therapy sessions and things that had been conducted over Zoom.

508
00:37:14,080 --> 00:37:18,600
And so I do think that there are problems here that do need addressing.

509
00:37:18,600 --> 00:37:24,540
But I entirely take the point, especially for the first Thursday, it sounded like it was by far the best tool for the job.

510
00:37:24,620 --> 00:37:27,420
But I do think you've just got to be careful and just be aware.

511
00:37:27,420 --> 00:37:30,080
And I will post links in the show notes to help you do that.

512
00:37:30,080 --> 00:37:34,680
Let's do a short Stay Insane in the Apocalypse bit to round out the show.

